    <h2>I work with start-ups, leaders, and teams to design meaningful ways of working that lead to better organizations and outcomes.</h2>

    <p>I believe that personal transformation is the foundation for meaningful organizational change. By starting with ourselves we can examine ingrained patterns of communicating, responding, and collaborating. As we start to understand and shift those patterns we experience new possibilities for how we show up, and in those possibilities are the seeds to larger change.</p>

    <p>Our organizations are relics of 19th century industrial ways of working, from structures to processes to operating principles. Here in the 21st century we've rapidly moved through waves of technological progress and the old ways of working no longer serve us. The metaphor of organization as machine has given way to organization as complex organism. Command-and-control bureaucracies are too slow and inflexible to respond to ever-changing market conditions. How do we co-create new ways of working that honors what it means to human and fosters continuous learning to create a competitive advantage?</p>


